<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910502-0067</DOCNO><DOCID>910502-0067.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Safety-Kleen Corp.:   California Health Division   Lodges Waste-Law Charges</HL><DATE>05/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SK</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)ILLINOIS (IL)</RE><LP>   The California Department of Health Services said it filedsuit against Safety-Kleen Corp., charging the company withabout 100 violations of state and federal hazardous wastelaws.   The department wants the court to order Safety-Kleen topay any penalties out of proceeds generated by any new stockofferings, in hopes of bringing shareholder pressure to bearon management. The department said the suit -- filed inAlameda County Superior Court and involving 10 facilities --was the second enforcement action in a year againstSafety-Kleen, an Elgin, Ill., car and industrial cleaningconcern. The department said Safety-Kleen was penalized$725,000 last May for violations at seven Californiafacilities.</LP><TEXT>   Safety-Kleen said &quot;a number&quot; of the allegations are&quot;incorrect.&quot; It said &quot;most&quot; of them involve &quot;the complex anddetailed paperwork requirements of California'shazardous-waste regulations.&quot;   The state said the alleged violations include a lack ofunderground tank-leak detection systems and the storage ofhazardous waste for longer periods and in greater quantitiesthan permitted.</TEXT></DOC>